40 WHEREAS, the General Assembly, of which the House of Representatives is a part, has "the
41 power to make all laws not inconsistent with this Constitution, and not repugnant to the
42 Constitution of the United States, which it shall deem necessary and proper for the welfare
43 of the state" according to Article III, Section VI, Paragraph I of the Georgia Constitution; and
44 WHEREAS, the Georgia Supreme Court, in Dean v. Bolton, 235 Ga. 544, held that
45 constitutional separation of powers does not prohibit the legislative branch from investigating
46 the official conduct of any person performing duties in any branch of the government; and
47 WHEREAS, the House of Representatives has the inherent power and authority to conduct
48 investigations into any matter relevant to the administration of existing laws, proposals for
49 new or amended laws, the expenditure of public funds, the conduct of public officers who
50 discharge powers and duties under state law, and any other matter germane to its role as part
51 of the legislative branch of state government; and
52
53 WHEREAS, such inherent powers also include the authority to create special committees for
54 the purpose of conducting investigations and to endow such committees with all the inherent
55 powers of investigation possessed by the House of Representatives, including the power to
56 compel the appearance and testimony of witnesses and the production of records and the
57 power to place witnesses under oath or affirmation; and
58 WHEREAS, in addition to such inherent powers, Code Sections 45-15-17 and 45-15-19
59 empower the General Assembly to make investigations into the affairs of the state and further
60 authorize compelling the appearance and testimony of witnesses and the production of
61 records and grants, the power to place witnesses under oath or affirmation, and the
62 enforcement of subpoenas issued pursuant thereto; and
